<div class="container">
  <div class="page-head">
    <h1>Features</h1>
    <p class="lede">Cueport reads your Serato library, lets you edit on your own terms in a local working layer, and pushes changes back when you ask. The release notes below cover what is in the current build.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature-list">
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Works with your Serato library</h3>
      <p>Link your <code>_Serato_</code> folder and Cueport reads your crates, subcrates, tracks, BPM, key, and color labels straight from Serato's own files on disk.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Reads cue points and notes</h3>
      <p>Hot cues come from Serato Markers in each MP3, and the track Comment field is read alongside them. What you see in Cueport matches what is in Serato.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Edit cues, notes, and collections</h3>
      <p>Add or move cue points, edit track notes inline, and create your own collections. Every edit stages in Cueport's local database with a clear sync status.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Push back to Serato</h3>
      <p>When you are ready, publish your staged edits back to the Serato MP3s and crate files. Pushes are per-connection and only happen when you ask.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Local playback with cues</h3>
      <p>Play tracks straight from your local files. The player shows the waveform, beatgrid, and your hot cues so you can audition without leaving the library.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Safety copies and restore points</h3>
      <p>Cueport duplicates <code>_Serato_</code> into Application Support after you link it and takes a fresh restore point before every push. Roll any publish back if you need to.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
